WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Alright, thanks everyone for joining us today for the RcppParallel webinar.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:15.000
RcppParallel being quite the tongue twister to say, so please forgive me if I mess that up a couple times during this presentation.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Alright, hopefully you are now seeing my screen and some slides on RcppParallel. Let's dive right in.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:31.000
Alright, so a brief introduction about why would you be interested or why would you care in RcppParallel.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Parallel and concurrent programming is a reality of modern software development and is necessary when developing high performance scientific software.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:51.000
So I've got here a quote from Herb Sutter who is kind of a C++ slash high performance computing guru over at Microsoft.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And he wrote in this article, Free Lunch is Over, that the performance lunch isn't free anymore.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
If you want your application to benefit from continued exponential throughput advances in new processors,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.000
it will need to be a well-written, concurrent, usually multi-threaded application.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And now this is a quote that comes from an essay written in 2004. That's like 12 years ago now.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:25.000
And while processors and compilers continue to improve, processor clock speed has hit a brick wall.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Processors basically haven't gotten much faster at all in the past 10 years.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.000
So we've had to look to other avenues for improving the performance of computer processors.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So you might be familiar with some of the packages for parallel computation with R.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:57.000
For example, the parallel package which I believe became part of R with 2.15 around that era of R.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.000
So R provides a number of packages that make it possible to run R code in parallel.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
So you might know about mcapply, clusterapply, parapply, those family of functions.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And what these functions do is they allow you to take R code and run it in separate R processes.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:24.000
These R processes running in parallel and then later collect the results from those processes back into a parent R process.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So if you have a cluster with a number of nodes, you might imagine sending a number of jobs to these separate nodes.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And each node here would be running this R code computer result and then send that back to the parent node or parent process.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And there is a CRAN task view that enumerates the number of R packages that help support different forms of parallel computing with R.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Now what rcppparallel does is a bit different from the R family of parallel packages.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:10.000
The goal in rcppparallel is not to execute R code in parallel, but to allow R to call lower level C or C++ code that is executed in parallel.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:17.000
So whether you're on, you know, say you've got a laptop with two or four cores or a desktop with four cores,

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:24.000
or you have some supercomputer that has, say, 32, 64 cores and a ton of memory,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:32.000
the goal of rcppparallel is to put those cores to their best use for whatever algorithms you're trying to implement.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Now, for those of you who haven't done much of this kind of lower level parallel or concurrent programming,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
unfortunately it's quite hard and this is a silly quote from a fellow named Ned Batchelor.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Some people when confronted with a problem think, I know, I'll use threads.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Now they have two problems.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
And the idea being here you have, if you ever have two threads or multiple threads,

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:08.000
multiple processes trying to write to standard output, you can get this weird interleaving of output

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
where the stuff you get back is just garbage, totally garbled.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.000
And that's kind of a common theme in parallel computing or concurrent programming.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.000
The hardest part is managing shared resources.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.000
In this case, the shared resource being the output stream that people are trying to write to,

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
or threads are trying to write to.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.000
And when you have multiple threads trying to write to standard output without appropriate locking

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
or threads taking ownership to say, okay, it's my turn to write and then releasing and let other people write,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.000
then you get these kinds of problems.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.000
So the goal of RCP parallel is to make it easier to write safe, correct, and perform in multi-threaded code

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
using C++ and RCPP and use that within an R session.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And more than that, it's to make sure that you, the user, don't have to worry about

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
this issues with contention over shared resources.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:12.000
For example, if you have an R object that you want to read or use for multiple processes,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
we want to give you some tools that make it easy to safely and performantly use that

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
on all of your cores on your machine.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Alright, so the way that RCP parallel does what it does is that it bundles two C++ libraries

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
that do most of the grunt work for parallel computation.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:44.000
So, the first one, Intel TBB, is a C++ library for task parallelism with a wide variety of parallel algorithms

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.000
and data structures.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And we've got this working on all of the major platforms, Windows, OSX, Linux, and even Solaris.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And so, in the most common case, you're going to be using Intel TBB threading building blocks

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
and this is the library that behind the scenes of RCP parallel is going to make sure that

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:12.000
when you designate a job that you want to run in parallel, it's going to do all the work of

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:19.000
spawning different threads and just making sure that your work runs in parallel and it runs fast.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:27.000
Now, we also bundle TinyThread which is a very small C++ library for the portable use of operating system threads.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:36.000
But nowadays, because Intel TBB is supported on all the platforms that are commonly used by R users,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
in general, you're going to be using Intel TBB.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Of course, as a user of RCP parallel, you don't need to dive into the internals of TBB

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
because we present a nice interface that I'll be showing soon.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.000
But it's good to know, you know, who's doing the heavy lifting behind the scenes.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Alright, so RCP parallel tries to solve, I guess it tries to provide interfaces for two main functions,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
for two common types of work that you might want to do in parallel.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
The first function we provide is a function called parallel for.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
The idea is that this will convert the work of a standard serial for loop into a parallel one.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:28.000
And the second one is parallel reduce which provides a way to compute and aggregate multiple values in parallel.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.000
So, these are functions provided by RCP parallel.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:40.000
And behind the scenes, they're going to delegate their work to the TBB Intel threading building blocks library.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So, the way that these functions work is effectively that they accept this thing that I'm going to call a worker object.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And this worker is going to know how to do work on a particular slice of data.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And I'll get into examples very soon.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Alright, so as a brief outline of how these functions work just to set the stage.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:10.000
Each of these functions accept a range of data to operate on.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:15.000
And a worker that understands how to do work on slices of that data.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.000
For example, the parallel for function.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:23.000
And I should just reiterate that this is a C++ function, not an R function.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:27.000
So, hopefully you have a bit of familiarity with C or C++.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:31.000
But this is just the signature of a function called parallel for.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
It's accepting a begin and an end index.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
Here the size T parameter being like an index parameter.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
And worker being the worker object I briefly discussed before.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.000
So, you're going to give this parallel for algorithm a range to operate on.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And a worker designation that knows how to do work within that range.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:05.000
So, as a user of RCP parallel, you can implement your own worker by subclassing this RCP parallel worker class.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And implementing the routines that do work on a slice of data.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:16.000
And so after you write the code that does the work and you call parallel for.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Behind the scenes, TBB is going to go ahead and generate multiple workers.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Divide them across your data and make sure that it's going to be responsible for making sure this worker runs in parallel.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:33.000
Or more accurately that multiple workers are generated to operate on slices of the data.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Alright, so let's start with a little example of how you might use a parallel worker.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Just to see how you would call it before we think about how we would implement a worker.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Alright, so first we're just going to look at, this is a little stub of C++ code.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Where we're trying to compute the log of a vector in parallel.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:06.000
So, if you've never seen C++ or RCP before.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.000
What we have here is just a stub for a worker class.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And I promise you, you'll see an implementation for this soon.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
But it's just something we're calling the log worker.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
And it inherits from the RCP parallel worker class.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
So this is our way of saying, okay, this is the log worker.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
This is the thing that's going to do work for computing the log on some range of data.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And here, this rcpp export attribute, I'll be showing you more later.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.000
But it's basically a way of saying, please make this available to the R session later.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And we've got a function that takes an rcpp numeric vector.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Think of it like a regular numeric vector in R.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And it's a wrapper to the same object.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And we've got our parallel log accepting some other numeric vector as input.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:01.000
So what we're going to do to compute our log on this numeric vector.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.000
Now, if you're working in the R world, everything is nicely vectorized for you.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
But in the C or C++ worlds, you're going to have to...

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Normally, what you would have to do is write a for loop to iterate over that.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:18.000
So you might have expected something like for i equals 0, i equals n, i plus plus.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
Compute the log of this element and set it somewhere.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:26.000
But for the rcpp parallel case, what we're going to do is pre-allocate our output vector.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
Have it be the same size as our input vector.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:34.000
And here, the no init is just a helper that says, just give me a chunk of memory.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.000
I'm going to fill it later.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
Don't worry about zero initializing it or anything like that.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
We're going to construct our log worker here.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
It's going to take our input vector.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And it's going to know how to fill the output vector.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:53.000
And then we call the parallel for function on the range of that vector with that worker.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
So that worker is going to know how to fill that output vector.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Okay.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
So let's see how we might implement that log worker.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:14.000
So, this is actually the whole implementation of how you might implement the log worker here.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:21.000
So first, we've got some, this is a little header that says, I'll show you in the IDE soon,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
that says, oh, this code snippet depends on rcpp parallel.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
We bring in the headers we're using, rcpp parallel and rcpp.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
Here, I'm just defining a small functor.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
It looks kind of weird, but just, if you're not familiar with this notation,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
just imagine that log here is like a function.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
Log is a function, a thing that can compute the log.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.000
And our log worker is going to accept instances of that to compute the log.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Alright.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
So, now let's look at our log worker.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Once, just to go back for a second, here we're going to fill in the blanks in here.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
So, we've got some members, input and output.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
There's going to be references to the r vectors, the input vector and output vector.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
Our constructor takes those and fills those.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And the reason why we use r vector here is just as a parallel safe version of the regular r numeric vector.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:32.000
rcpp parallel tries to give you these safe wrappers to r objects that you know can be used safely in parallel.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
Because if you try to use arbitrary elements of the r API,

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
you can run into trouble if you're using those in a parallel worker.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:46.000
In general, the code that you put in an rcpp parallel worker should not touch the r API directly.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:53.000
You should stick with the C++ functions or other C++ libraries available in language.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Alright.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.000
So, we've got our constructor.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
This is how our log worker is made.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
It just stores references to the input and output.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
And here is where we define our work.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.000
This is the implementation for a worker to do work on some slice of data.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:15.000
So, if you haven't seen this thing before, it's basically a way of saying,

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
okay, I want this class to behave kind of like a function.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
I want this objects of this class to be callable.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.000
So, when you call this worker, this is the function that would get called.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And so, this operator, it doesn't return anything.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.000
So, whatever it's doing, it's doing as a side effect.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:41.000
And the things that it takes in are indices being the begin and end,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
like the slice of data that the worker should work on.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And here, I'm using a STL algorithms did transform that takes input iterators

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:57.000
and an output iterator and a function to apply as it goes through.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
So, each worker is going to do a bunch of work in serial.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.000
But behind the scenes, Parallel 4 is generating a whole bunch of these workers

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
that will do this work across different slices of data.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.000
And they'll do those work in parallel.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:21.000
So, as a quick micro benchmark that I did beforehand,

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.000
if you want to compare this to just computing the log in R

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:29.000
and using our parallel log function in RCP parallel,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
if we took a little micro benchmark, you'd see that our parallel solution,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
and this is on a MacBook Pro having four processors.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:42.000
We might expect, in the best case, we'd get four times performance.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
Of course, in practice, you won't see a...

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:50.000
You'll see a bit of drop-off as you scale parallel algorithms to the number of cores you have.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
But it should still be a significant benefit.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:59.000
But what we see here is that our parallel log is roughly three times faster than R's log.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
So, that's a nice one.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:09.000
Just to dive into the details, I don't want to go too deep here yet

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
because we've got documentation online.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
I just want to focus on the high-level stuff.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:18.000
But RCP parallel uses TBB in almost all scenarios.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
And that comes with highly optimized execution scheduler.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
And it does intelligent optimization around the grain size,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
which affects locality of reference, and therefore cache hit rates.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:33.000
If you're familiar with modern architectures of processors,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:38.000
you know that memory is now hierarchical.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
You've got L1 caches, L2 caches, L3 caches.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:47.000
And the goal is to make sure that you fill the L1 cache and use all the data in there.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:51.000
If not, you fill the L2 cache and use all the data in there.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:54.000
If you're missing those caches, if you have to go back to main memory

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.000
to get data and fill back the cache, you're going to have cache misses,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
which are bad for performance.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:07.000
So, TBB, roughly speaking, does its best to make sure that you don't have cache misses.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
And finally, it also helps with work stealing.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
It tries to detect if there's idle threads and say,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
hey, wake up, I've got some work for you to do.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And this can all be tuned in RCP parallel, although I might not get to it in this webinar.

