00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:59.000
there's usually this kind of painful build iteration in C++

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:03.000
in that you have to compile your C++ files, you have to link it,

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.000
and then you maybe have a test harness or something you run.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:14.000
But, it's really nice in the IDE that you can just take your C++ file

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.000
and source it and run it directly in the IDE.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
It couldn't be simpler.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:29.000
Alright, so I showed a brief example of the parallel for.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:33.000
Let's jump over to the parallel reduce.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:36.000
For this example, I'll compute the inner product.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:42.000
So, if you recall, the inner product of two vectors is effectively what you get

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:46.000
if you multiply each element in those two vectors element-wise

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
and then sum those products up.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:56.000
So, here I've got my little R implementation of how you might do that.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:01.000
It's nice and small and succinct, but that's not going to be running in parallel.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:04.000
So, let's see how we might do that in parallel with RSVP parallel.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
Alright, so first we're going to define a little function product

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:13.000
just so we have something that we can pass to our inner product worker.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.000
So, product is a function that takes two doubles and returns a product.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.000
Nice and simple.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:22.000
And here we're going to have our inner product worker

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.000
and that's going to once again inherit from RSVP parallel worker.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:33.000
Up here, I've got our private numbers LHS I say for left-hand side,

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
RHS for right-hand side.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:39.000
So, these are going to be our R vector inputs.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:42.000
And then output, because we're computing a scalar value,

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.000
I'm going to compute a double output value.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:50.000
So, the first thing that we have is our regular constructor.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.000
It takes a numeric vector on the left-hand side,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:57.000
numeric vector on the right-hand side, and it fills these values.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:00.000
We'll come back to this constructor in a bit,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:06.000
but it'll be important when we understand how the reduce stage of this operation happens.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:13.000
But let's look at the call operator for this class.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:20.000
And so, each worker given a range, it's going to try and fill this output value.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:25.000
And the C++ standard library, it actually comes with an algorithm

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
for computing the inner product.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:31.000
So, we can call that directly over the range that we've been provided.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:37.000
So, because these are std size T, they're numeric indexes,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:41.000
we want to pass iterators to inner product.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.000
What we're going to do here is call LHS.begin,

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
which is the very start of the left-hand side vector,

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:55.000
and then nudge that iterator forward to the actual beginning of the range we want to work on.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:59.000
And then similar here, we want to give it the end of the range to work on.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:07.000
And here is the right-hand side range for when it computes the product of elements.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:10.000
And 0.0 here is just a starting value.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:18.000
Alright, so now each worker is going to be filling its own output value.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:23.000
So, this value, remember when we call parallelReduce,

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.000
multiple workers are going to be generated,

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
and they're all going to be filling their own output value.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:33.000
So, depending on how many workers get generated, there might be 4 or 8.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
There's going to be 4 or 8 of these values.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:40.000
So, what we need to know is how can we join these values together at the end.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:47.000
So, we've got these kind of mini inner products on different ranges of the data,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:51.000
different slices of the data, and we want to join those together.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:55.000
And we do that by implementing this join function down here.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
And it's kind of, it's relatively simple.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:04.000
What you have here is a function called join that accepts some other worker.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:12.000
And the idea is that this worker is going to provide the result of its work to the active worker.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:18.000
And to do that, all we have to do is add the output that's been computed by the other worker

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.000
right to this own output here.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.000
All right.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:32.000
And now, knowing that we have this join here, this constructor that we have here,

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
it's kind of just, you can almost think of it as boilerplate.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:44.000
It's just the magic constructor that's used so that RSVP Parallel knows how to split up workers

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
in the parallelReduce scenario.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:52.000
And what we have in here is, it's kind of like a copy constructor.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:00.000
Here, we initialize the left-hand side with the contents of the other inner product worker's left-hand side.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:03.000
Same with the right-hand side and the output.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:05.000
All right.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
So, like we did before, I'm going to take this.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.000
I'm going to set source on save.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
I'm going to hit Command-S.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:16.000
Well, first, I'll clear the console with Control-L, and I'll Command-S to source it.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.000
We've got some R code at the bottom that's going to run in a similar way

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
to compute the inner product in parallel.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:26.000
All right.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:31.000
So, once again, we can convince ourselves that, yes, we are computing with correct value.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:36.000
And if we run a little microbenchmark, we'll actually see, oh my gosh,

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
we're almost 10 times faster than what R is doing here.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:45.000
And so, I'm on a laptop with only four cores, so there must be something else going on here.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:51.000
Actually, what's happening in R, you can imagine that when you compute LHS times RHS,

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:59.000
what you have is another numeric vector of the same length of the LHS and RHS vectors.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:05.000
So, you're computing a whole new vector, and then you're finally reducing or collapsing that by calling sum.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:14.000
But in our parallel worker case, because we're just filling one single output on each worker directly,

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:18.000
we're not generating a whole new vector of the same sizes or inputs.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:24.000
We get a bit of memory savings in addition to the parallel processing improvements.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:30.000
So, there are some very nice gains to be realized with RSP Parallel,

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:35.000
even on your own commodity hardware, but you can imagine that it will scale,

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:43.000
and it does scale, in fact, on larger machines or supercomputers, computers with many processors.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
All right.

