00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:26.000
Okay, so now how did we make that happen?

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:34.000
So, in an R package, when you have compiled code or C or C++ code, you always put it in the source folder.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:40.000
And, in our source folder, I have pretty much the same log and inner product files that we've seen before.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:43.000
So, let's take a quick look at the log file.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:47.000
All this stuff up here, it's exactly as we saw before.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:50.000
Here, this is something a little different.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:58.000
This, if you're familiar with ROxygen, which is a way of documenting functions and classes in R files,

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:01.000
you can actually do the same thing in C++ files.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:07.000
And, if you're using dev tools to document, it'll parse those ROxygen comments,

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:13.000
these C++ ROxygen comments, and promote them to the exported R wrappers.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:18.000
So, what we have here is effectively just the documentation for this parallel log.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:22.000
It's a simple function. It computes just the natural log of a numeric vector.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:26.000
It takes a numeric vector as input.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:32.000
And, this export declaration here says the R wrapper that we generate, we should export it.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:38.000
Now, this is a little bit confusing in that we have two export statements.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:43.000
But, here, this one is saying for the generated R function, make that exported.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:49.000
I.e., when someone loads this package, I want the R wrapper function to be visible to them.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:53.000
And, this one is saying, well, this function that we've got here,

00:30:53.000 --> 00:31:00.000
we want to make the C++ interface available to the R package.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:05.000
So, this is a little bit lower level and this is a way of saying the parallel log function should be generated.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:08.000
The R wrapper function should be generated.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:13.000
But, this is saying that the generated R wrapper function should be exported.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:17.000
And, let me just jump to show you that's true.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:23.000
So, this rctbexports.r file, which is auto-generated for us based on the contents of this file.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:32.000
What we see here is, in our parallel log, is the exact same ROxygen documentation that we discussed before.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:36.000
And, this little wrapper function using .call is a way of saying,

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:41.000
I want to call some compiled code with a function of this name in this package.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:46.000
So, all you need to know is that this stuff is done behind the scenes for you.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:52.000
And, all you need to worry about is writing your own C++ files with these annotations

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:58.000
that tell the Rcpp package in RStudio how to build the wrapper functions.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:07.000
So, given that, what we have in here is exactly the same as what we had before.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:11.000
For our inner product, same thing.

