Parallel log displayed nicely in the RStudio help pane.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:44.000
Alright, so, there's a number of kind of fiddly prerequisites to R packages using Rcpparallel

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:47.000
and you have to make sure to follow each of them.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:51.000
Otherwise, unfortunately, you can bump into strange errors.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.000
And, one of them is how you construct your namespace file.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:04.000
So, this namespace file, it tells our, well, how to construct the namespace of your package

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:07.000
and that includes what functions should be exported

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:11.000
or what functions or objects should be imported from other packages.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:17.000
So, the first thing we'll do here is, I know I talked about the Rock Street and Commons before,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:19.000
everything super simple in our namespace.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:24.000
What we're actually doing is using this export pattern to say everything that doesn't start with a dot,

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:27.000
I want that made available to users of our package.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:34.000
So, this is the declaration that says the parallel inner product and parallel log R wrapper function

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
should be made available to users of the package.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:45.000
Now, this one is a little scary and I actually bumped into this while preparing the webinar

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
for the Rcpparallel talk.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:51.000
So, if anything, it's pretty important to follow directions.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:55.000
Otherwise, unfortunately, you will see some strange things.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:01.000
And, if you try to build your package, let me see if I can actually just remove these

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.000
and convince you that strange things go wrong.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:10.000
You clean and rebuild this, see all this compiler output.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:14.000
Build it and, ooh, something bizarre went wrong.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:18.000
And so, you see this here, this symbol not found task.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:19.000
It's like a mangled name.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:25.000
It's a mangled name of the function that it's trying to call and saying, oh, that thing doesn't exist.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:32.000
And, that's basically because when the package is being built and loaded,

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:39.000
the Rcpparallel package isn't loaded alongside it so that the routines in the Rcpparallel package,

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:43.000
which our example package is using, are not available.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:48.000
So, Rcpparallel loads our package and says, hey, where's this symbol that I'm looking for?

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
I expect it in Rcpparallel.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:55.000
Well, the way to make sure that Rcpparallel is there and is providing the symbol for you

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:59.000
is just to import any object from that package.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:02.000
And, here, I'm importing the Rcpparallel libs.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:06.000
We do a similar thing from Rcpp for the same reasons.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:09.000
Let me just rebuild that, convince you that it does fix things.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:15.000
And, there we go.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
We've got our package built and ready to go.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:19.000
All right.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:27.000
And, the final little one in your namespace is it's somewhat bizarre that you have to add this

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:30.000
since you would think that, oh, my package has C++ code.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
It has compiled code.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:39.000
It's the shared object, the file that houses these compiled routines is being made,

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
generated for the package.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:48.000
But, yet, I still have to tell R explicitly, oh, I'm building a library of compiled functions

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
and I want to use it.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:54.000
So, unfortunately, R doesn't do this automatically for you in your namespace file.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:59.000
You need to make sure that you say, use dynlib, which just says, okay, I know I'm generating.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.000
I've got my package has compiled code.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
I want to actually use it.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
I'm not just compiling it for fun.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:12.000
So, if you're building a package that has compiled code, which in this case is using Rcpparallel,

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:16.000
you'll need to make sure that you have this use dynlib declaration.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:24.000
So, the reason why I'm spending time on this is just because these are the most common stumbling blocks

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:27.000
when getting started with Rcpparallel.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Once you have the template and once you have, like I hope some of you who are interested in using Rcpparallel,

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:38.000
you can just copy this package, start tweaking some of the files, maybe add some of your own

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:42.000
and see how it works as you play around.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:47.000
The last thing I'll look at in here is these makevars files.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:55.000
So, here, the makevars files are kind of our way of setting certain variables

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:58.000
that affect how your package is compiled.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:04.000
makevars for non-Windows platforms and makevars.win for Windows platforms.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:10.000
So, nowadays, you actually don't really need this, but I'm going to include this

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:14.000
just because it's nice to have it for backwards compatibility with Rcpparallel.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:21.000
But, when you build your package, you basically want to tell R that the package lives environment variable.

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:25.000
You want to tell it that, oh yeah, Rcpparallel is providing some libraries

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:28.000
and make sure that during compilation those are used.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.000
So, in practice, on non-Windows machines, you don't need this nowadays.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:42.000
But, on Windows machines, you do need a makevars.win and that's for backwards compatibility reasons.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:48.000
So, back in the early days of Rcpparallel, Windows was not supported as a platform

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:55.000
just because development on Windows is often a little more difficult than other platforms.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:59.000
So, nowadays, TBB is supported on Windows.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:06.000
But, just to ensure that your package works with newer versions of R and Rcpparallel,

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:13.000
you need to explicitly say this "-d means define a variable and Rcpparallel use TBB.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.000
Please use TBB in my package," and you attach that to your CXX flags.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:21.000
And then, similarly, this is the same thing as we saw before,

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:27.000
except a little bit more boilerplate and constructing paths to the R script executable.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:33.000
And this is saying, make sure that we use the Rcpparallel libs libraries when you compile my package.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:50.000
So, with those caveats, which there are a few of them, but once you know them,

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
then you know not to bump into them.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:58.000
It's really quite easy to use Rcpparallel in your own code and in your own packages.

