So, if you saw in my log and inner product examples,

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:20.000
what we have on the Rcpp gallery is basically a lot of similar things to that.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:24.000
So, we've got inner product here, parallel distant matrix computation.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
Let's take a quick look at that.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:31.000
So, what you have here in the Rcpp gallery is these nice articles that stand alone.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:37.000
They present some R and C++ code using Rcpp or Rcpparallel,

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:43.000
and this can give you very good ideas about, you know, how are other people using Rcpparallel

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:47.000
and how can I use it myself for some of the things I want to do.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:54.000
So, from one user, he asks, can we parallelize a task across several computers?

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:57.000
And the answer for this is no.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:03.000
So, the goal of Rcpparallel is to use all of the processors on one machine.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:11.000
Now, you can combine this with, for example, the parallel computation packages provided by R.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:15.000
So, you can imagine taking a compiled routine that knows how to use the cores,

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:20.000
all of the cores on one machine and compute that in parallel across multiple machines.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:25.000
So, Rcpparallel takes care of the parallelism per machine

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:29.000
and the Rparallel libraries take care of parallelism across machines.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:32.000
And that's the way I would prefer to think about it.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.000
So, one question.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:40.000
Rcpparallel essentially interfaces R with TBB with only two specialized Rcpparallel functions,

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.000
ParallelFor and ParallelReduce.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:43.000
That's correct.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:51.000
These are kind of solving the, we call them the embarrassingly parallel problems in computation,

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:58.000
but because it bundles the TBB package, everything that TBB has is available for you.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:03.000
So, if you're a power user and we outline a little bit of this on the GitHub repo,

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:08.000
there's a whole bunch of tools available in TBB for concurrent programming.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:13.000
So, once you feel like saying, okay, I care enough to build my own locks, my own queues.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:19.000
I want to take more control of how this task is executed in parallel.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:24.000
Because the Rcpparallel makes TBB available, you can just use that directly.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:29.000
So, we have some brief documentations for kind of diving a little bit deeper with that.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
We have one question.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:35.000
How does this package relate to using Spark in R?

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:39.000
And so, these are effectively, you know, unrelated.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:45.000
Spark is kind of a platform for big data and machine learning with large data sets.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:52.000
It provides nice, you know, interfaces, SQL interfaces, different programming interfaces to manipulating that data.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:57.000
But that lives outside of R.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:06.000
There's, you know, packages like sparklyr4, which is a new package introduced by RStudio for interacting with Spark from RStudio.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:11.000
But the goal of Rcpparallel is not interacting with the external database,

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:15.000
but interacting with the data you have in memory on your machine.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:20.000
There's one question about how can we implement MapReduce using Rcpparallel.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:25.000
The idea, if you want to do that, that's basically what ParallelReduce is doing.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:33.000
The work information, that operator, open paren, close paren, that's the map function.

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:36.000
That's the transformation you're doing on some range of data.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:41.000
And then the join function, that's how you're reducing or combining the results from there.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:47.000
So, MapReduce is totally possible, although we don't give it the same MapReduce name.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:56.000
One question, is it good practice to use all but say one core?

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:59.000
And that's kind of a tough question.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:07.000
The general issue here is with parallel computation,

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:12.000
you generally don't scale linearly as you increase the number of cores, unfortunately.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:19.000
So, the gain you get from going from one to four cores might not be as much as the gain from going from four to eight cores.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:24.000
Although, in this case, because we're working on so-called embarrassingly parallel problems

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:28.000
where there's very little contention between the different workers,

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:34.000
you should see relatively high gains close to linear as you increase the number of processors.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:42.000
But, in general, you have to tune that yourself and Rcpparallel and TBB provide APIs for tuning that.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:46.000
Alright, I will take one more question.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:51.000
The question here is, can Rcpparallel be used on do or while loops or only for?

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:57.000
And, so, Rcpparallel kind of takes the work that might be done by a for loop

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:00.000
and gives you a way of expressing that in parallel.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:08.000
And, most do or while loops probably have an equivalent way of expressing them with a for loop

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:12.000
that might not be as obvious but should be possible.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:20.000
So, in general, I guess I wouldn't think of it in terms of, you know, I want to convert a for loop into a parallel for.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:23.000
I'd say, I have a range of data.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:29.000
I want to apply the same operation on each element in that range of data

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:32.000
and I want that computation to be done in parallel.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:36.000
So, Rcpparallel gives you a mechanism for doing that.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
Alright, with that, I will finish the webinar.

